reviews.review_text: Damn This To Lay Me Down still brings me to tears.

The recording is warm rather than tinny, but the high end is so indistinct that I can't really tell what kind of a show it was. What I can hear suggests good rather than spectacular, as is typical with shows picked for publishing. The fact that the Miller SBD version is the highest rated show of the year is an indication of the low quality of the year rather than the high quality of the music. I know, I was there.

Yeah, and if you can't have a better reason for how you review a show than that whoever disagrees with you is an idiot, you're basically a religious fanatic who backs up their opinion with threats of violence ("you will like this show or you will be called an idiot"). I have reasons for what I say that have nothing to do with what you think rocks, and that's how it should be: otherwise no Deadhead would be different from another. Um...

Fabulous. njpg..

If you were there, you're a bigger idiot than I thought you were when I first read your post..

Just because you were there doesn't mean you know anything. .

What I would give to relive 1985, and all the amazing music that came along with it..

Byrne always rocked. .I know this to be true because I was there, as well..
